1
00:00:04,130 --> 00:00:05,479
Are you doing alright?

2
00:00:05,480 --> 00:00:06,680
I'm fine.

3
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:12,309
Believe it or not, I used to be a
camera operator when I first started.

4
00:00:12,310 --> 00:00:13,280
Whoa, hold on.

5
00:00:13,281 --> 00:00:14,300
Sorry.

6
00:00:14,310 --> 00:00:16,040
You're making me even more nervous.

7
00:00:16,140 --> 00:00:18,510
What matters most are words.

8
00:00:19,300 --> 00:00:20,800
As an individual,

9
00:00:21,120 --> 00:00:24,520
I want to face another individual
with complete sincerity.

10
00:00:25,780 --> 00:00:30,000
What I want today isn't to film,
but to have a conversation.

11
00:00:31,720 --> 00:00:33,420
You've changed.

12
00:00:33,460 --> 00:00:34,460
Kayano-san.

13
00:00:37,370 --> 00:00:39,940
Shall we get started then?

14
00:00:41,960 --> 00:00:43,009
Yes.

15
00:00:43,010 --> 00:00:43,760
(Day 100)

16
00:00:43,761 --> 00:00:45,340
I'm ready.

17
00:00:46,900 --> 00:00:49,010
Whenever you're ready.

18
00:00:57,480 --> 00:00:59,090
I am truly sorry.

19
00:01:01,220 --> 00:01:04,220
Hasegawa Itsuki and I, Kasuga Yuma,

20
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:07,229
when we started filming this documentary,

21
00:01:07,230 --> 00:01:11,400
were actually no longer a couple.

22
00:01:13,820 --> 00:01:15,240
We were living together...

23
00:01:15,820 --> 00:01:19,339
because Itsuki couldn't pay his rent and was
about to get kicked out of his apartment.

24
00:01:19,340 --> 00:01:21,910
So, I invited him to move in with me.

25
00:01:24,500 --> 00:01:26,950
He's just the kind of person
who lets things get that bad.

26
00:01:26,980 --> 00:01:29,520
So... yeah, he was really irresponsible.

27
00:01:32,180 --> 00:01:35,560
What did you think of Hasegawa-san
back then?

28
00:01:35,800 --> 00:01:36,800
Well...

29
00:01:37,740 --> 00:01:41,360
When we first moved in, I think I found
that side of him charming.

30
00:01:42,640 --> 00:01:46,699
But gradually, I started thinking about
how to change things.

31
00:01:46,700 --> 00:01:48,870
So, I applied for a partnership oath.

32
00:01:50,140 --> 00:01:51,570
I thought that if we took the oath,

33
00:01:51,640 --> 00:01:54,710
and became a publicly recognized couple,

34
00:01:54,740 --> 00:01:57,380
maybe Itsuki would change his lifestyle.

35
00:01:58,010 --> 00:02:00,220
That was how shallow
my thinking was back then.

36
00:02:01,780 --> 00:02:08,360
But the one who actually changed... was me.

37
00:02:11,340 --> 00:02:15,630
After our interview video went viral,
everyone put us on a pedestal.

38
00:02:16,130 --> 00:02:20,170
Being seen as the ideal gay couple
made me feel so proud.

39
00:02:21,600 --> 00:02:25,140
I felt this intense pressure
not to let everyone down.

40
00:02:27,040 --> 00:02:28,340
But that guy...

41
00:02:28,920 --> 00:02:33,550
Literally the next day,
he said he was exhausted

42
00:02:33,580 --> 00:02:35,820
and quit his part-time job
at the convenience store.

43
00:02:36,740 --> 00:02:38,250
I was absolutely furious.

44
00:02:39,390 --> 00:02:41,189
I gave him an ultimatum.

45
00:02:41,190 --> 00:02:44,056
If he couldn't keep his next job for
at least a year, he had to move out.

46
00:02:44,080 --> 00:02:49,830
Itsuki agreed
and started working at a bar.

47
00:02:50,620 --> 00:02:55,100
But sure enough, he quit again
after only a month.

48
00:02:55,960 --> 00:03:00,210
Looking back, though,
he did have his reasons for quitting.

49
00:03:01,480 --> 00:03:04,480
And that's when you were approached
about the documentary?

50
00:03:05,060 --> 00:03:05,880
Yes.

51
00:03:05,881 --> 00:03:07,750
Why did you decide to agree to it?

52
00:03:09,800 --> 00:03:12,890
It's not like I didn't want to
raise awareness for sexual minorities,

53
00:03:13,720 --> 00:03:18,530
or show appreciation to
those who supported us.

54
00:03:20,400 --> 00:03:23,330
But more than any of that...

55
00:03:23,370 --> 00:03:25,370
the biggest reason was...

56
00:03:27,800 --> 00:03:29,370
I just...

57
00:03:30,880 --> 00:03:32,270
I really just...

58
00:03:34,120 --> 00:03:37,710
didn't want to break up with Itsuki.

59
00:03:40,980 --> 00:03:45,800
I was terrified of our story
just ending like that.

60
00:03:46,990 --> 00:03:50,160
So I used the filming of this documentary

61
00:03:50,190 --> 00:03:52,860
to force our story to keep going.

62
00:03:52,900 --> 00:03:54,560
That's how I felt at the time.

63
00:03:56,180 --> 00:03:57,180
But...

64
00:03:58,120 --> 00:03:59,840
the end was inevitable.

65
00:04:00,840 --> 00:04:04,310
And this interview is our final chapter.

66
00:04:07,840 --> 00:04:09,650
We are ending things today.

67
00:04:10,860 --> 00:04:14,520
Itsuki has already moved
his things to his new place.

68
00:04:14,960 --> 00:04:19,520
Now, all that's left is for
him to walk out the door.

69
00:04:23,500 --> 00:04:26,860
I think there are people
like me everywhere.

70
00:04:27,130 --> 00:04:29,980
Oh, I don't mean being a sexual minority.

71
00:04:31,400 --> 00:04:34,236
I mean people who think, 'If we
just get married, things will work out, '

72
00:04:34,260 --> 00:04:36,510
or 'If we have a kid,
maybe things will get better.'

73
00:04:36,980 --> 00:04:41,640
Acting on such shallow thoughts,
only to fail or succeed in the end.

74
00:04:44,500 --> 00:04:49,320
I'm just one of the countless
ordinary people in this world.

75
00:04:50,720 --> 00:04:51,720
So...

76
00:04:51,940 --> 00:04:53,980
just because things didn't work out for us,

77
00:04:55,020 --> 00:04:59,490
it doesn't mean people like us
don't need these systems.

78
00:05:01,600 --> 00:05:04,600
It's not because we're special
that we need to be protected.

79
00:05:05,940 --> 00:05:08,069
It's because we aren't special

80
00:05:08,070 --> 00:05:10,870
that we want to be allowed to do
what everyone else takes for granted.

81
00:05:11,640 --> 00:05:15,840
That's what partnerships and
same-sex marriage are all about.

82
00:05:19,980 --> 00:05:23,350
'I wish we had never
taken that partnership oath.'

83
00:05:23,680 --> 00:05:25,720
'I wish we had never
done that interview.'

84
00:05:26,340 --> 00:05:28,820
'I wish I hadn't gotten so angry
when he quit his job.'

85
00:05:30,820 --> 00:05:34,430
'I wish we had turned down
this documentary.'

86
00:05:36,600 --> 00:05:38,700
I've had all those thoughts.

87
00:05:39,860 --> 00:05:41,170
But not anymore.

88
00:05:42,500 --> 00:05:45,009
Because we were fundamentally incompatible.

89
00:05:45,010 --> 00:05:47,619
No matter which path we took,

90
00:05:47,620 --> 00:05:51,280
I think we would have ended up here anyway.

91
00:05:54,360 --> 00:05:58,390
Do you ever wish
you had never dated him?

92
00:05:58,800 --> 00:06:00,520
Well...

93
00:06:01,600 --> 00:06:02,600
If...

94
00:06:03,990 --> 00:06:05,990
I could go back to
before we started dating,

95
00:06:06,930 --> 00:06:10,100
with all the memories I have now...

96
00:06:13,970 --> 00:06:16,510
I think... I would still date Itsuki.

97
00:06:19,290 --> 00:06:23,709
And this time, I'd struggle desperately
not to make the same mistakes,

98
00:06:23,710 --> 00:06:26,520
only to realize all over again
that we are fundamentally incompatible.

99
00:06:27,170 --> 00:06:29,320
And then we'd break up, just like this.

100
00:06:32,520 --> 00:06:34,320
It sounds pretty foolish, though.

101
00:06:38,570 --> 00:06:39,969
Did Yama-chan buy this?

102
00:06:39,970 --> 00:06:40,970
Yeah.

103
00:06:44,250 --> 00:06:45,250
He has terrible taste.

104
00:06:45,251 --> 00:06:46,300
Hey!

105
00:06:47,050 --> 00:06:48,730
Seriously, you've been so critical lately.

106
00:06:49,030 --> 00:06:50,030
Itsuki.

107
00:06:51,070 --> 00:06:52,910
- Your turn.
- Got it.

108
00:06:54,530 --> 00:06:55,740
I'm ready.

109
00:06:56,410 --> 00:06:58,290
Welcome to Cafe Yamada.

110
00:06:58,310 --> 00:06:59,330
Please, have a seat.

111
00:07:01,750 --> 00:07:03,190
Thanks for your hard work.

112
00:07:03,220 --> 00:07:04,589
Ah, thank you.

113
00:07:04,590 --> 00:07:05,590
Yeah.

114
00:07:10,460 --> 00:07:13,830
This is such a cozy home.

115
00:07:14,790 --> 00:07:16,309
It is.

116
00:07:16,310 --> 00:07:17,970
I really like it here.

117
00:07:18,930 --> 00:07:21,640
What about you, Yamada?
What kind of place do you live in?

118
00:07:22,770 --> 00:07:24,770
It's cheap, tiny, and old.

119
00:07:26,070 --> 00:07:31,550
The tenants are incredibly diverse. It's
practically the definition of 'diversity.'

120
00:07:31,610 --> 00:07:34,020
And the neighbors interact a lot.

121
00:07:35,410 --> 00:07:36,920
Diversity, huh?

122
00:07:38,070 --> 00:07:44,090
But what does 'embracing diversity'
actually mean?

123
00:07:44,560 --> 00:07:45,560
Hmm?

124
00:07:45,930 --> 00:07:47,690
There are all kinds
of people in this world.

125
00:07:47,760 --> 00:07:50,100
Some you get along with,
and some you don't.

126
00:07:50,310 --> 00:07:52,500
But that's just how it is, right?

127
00:07:52,770 --> 00:07:54,276
Does accepting diversity
mean we have to force ourselves

128
00:07:54,300 --> 00:07:57,070
to talk to people we don't get along with?

129
00:07:59,310 --> 00:08:00,580
Well...

130
00:08:05,290 --> 00:08:07,350
The world is naturally diverse.

131
00:08:07,950 --> 00:08:09,430
That's just a simple fact.

132
00:08:10,830 --> 00:08:15,390
Just like the Earth rotating,
that's just how it works.

133
00:08:16,690 --> 00:08:18,830
Just as we accept that the Earth rotates,

134
00:08:19,210 --> 00:08:21,530
we accept the diversity of this world.

135
00:08:22,850 --> 00:08:25,970
Whether we get along or
treat each other with kindness

136
00:08:26,370 --> 00:08:28,040
is something that comes after that.

137
00:08:32,630 --> 00:08:34,430
- You know...
- Yes?

138
00:08:34,940 --> 00:08:36,620
I actually can't handle carbonated drinks.

139
00:08:37,930 --> 00:08:38,930
That was so passionate.

140
00:08:38,950 --> 00:08:40,250
What kind of reaction is that?

141
00:08:41,450 --> 00:08:42,949
Sorry to keep you waiting.

142
00:08:42,950 --> 00:08:44,050
Oh, thank you.

143
00:08:44,320 --> 00:08:45,320
Here you go.

144
00:08:46,970 --> 00:08:49,269
- So this is the legendary...
- Legendary?

145
00:08:49,270 --> 00:08:51,500
Well, let's eat.

146
00:08:51,530 --> 00:08:52,709
Let's eat.

147
00:08:52,710 --> 00:08:53,799
Awesome.

148
00:08:53,800 --> 00:08:54,600
Alright.

149
00:08:54,630 --> 00:08:56,030
This is great!

150
00:08:56,290 --> 00:08:57,290
Wow, this is huge!

151
00:09:05,310 --> 00:09:06,629
- Huh?
- Hmm?

152
00:09:06,630 --> 00:09:08,609
Do you put soy sauce on your croquettes?

153
00:09:08,610 --> 00:09:10,049
Huh? You don't?

154
00:09:10,050 --> 00:09:11,419
No, I don't.

155
00:09:11,420 --> 00:09:12,879
What?! Really?

156
00:09:12,880 --> 00:09:14,589
This guy only uses ketchup.

157
00:09:14,590 --> 00:09:15,849
Huh?

158
00:09:15,850 --> 00:09:17,250
Usually, you use sauce, right?

159
00:09:17,390 --> 00:09:20,009
Actually, they taste best plain.

160
00:09:20,010 --> 00:09:21,739
He always says that.

161
00:09:21,740 --> 00:09:22,740
Really?

162
00:09:23,150 --> 00:09:24,590
Just try it first.

163
00:10:10,430 --> 00:10:11,430
Okay.

164
00:10:12,470 --> 00:10:13,910
I'm off.

165
00:10:15,670 --> 00:10:16,680
Yeah...

166
00:10:18,130 --> 00:10:19,820
Ah, wait.

167
00:10:20,730 --> 00:10:21,750
Hmm?

168
00:10:24,390 --> 00:10:27,390
Could you throw this away somewhere?

169
00:10:27,450 --> 00:10:29,503
(Partnership Application Form)

170
00:10:32,370 --> 00:10:35,189
Huh? Don't we have to
return this to the ward office?

171
00:10:35,190 --> 00:10:36,930
Yeah, the certificate has to be returned.

172
00:10:37,530 --> 00:10:39,030
But we get to keep this part.

173
00:10:39,790 --> 00:10:40,790
Please.

174
00:10:41,310 --> 00:10:45,040
I just can't bring myself to throw it away.

175
00:10:48,390 --> 00:10:51,790
Then don't.

176
00:10:52,550 --> 00:10:53,550
Huh?

177
00:10:54,050 --> 00:10:56,050
Just get rid of it when you're ready.

178
00:10:58,010 --> 00:10:59,560
If you can't do it now,

179
00:11:00,450 --> 00:11:02,290
it means you still need it.

180
00:11:05,470 --> 00:11:06,470
Is that okay?

181
00:11:08,260 --> 00:11:09,600
Why wouldn't it be?

182
00:11:15,370 --> 00:11:21,080
If... same-sex marriage
were legal in Japan,

183
00:11:21,830 --> 00:11:25,510
and what we submitted back then
was a marriage registration...

184
00:11:27,470 --> 00:11:30,570
would you still have wanted

185
00:11:31,590 --> 00:11:33,520
to be with me?

186
00:11:35,120 --> 00:11:36,560
Well...

187
00:11:39,750 --> 00:11:40,750
Probably...

188
00:11:41,930 --> 00:11:44,399
when you proposed to me,

189
00:11:44,400 --> 00:11:45,970
I would have said no.

190
00:11:50,970 --> 00:11:52,040
You jerk.

191
00:11:57,110 --> 00:12:00,779
In that case, instead of taking this oath,

192
00:12:00,780 --> 00:12:04,250
it would've been better if you'd
just rejected me from the start.

193
00:12:04,710 --> 00:12:06,310
Then I wouldn't have had any false hope.

194
00:12:10,950 --> 00:12:11,950
No.

195
00:12:14,680 --> 00:12:20,200
Having the chance to fail properly
is an important right, too.

196
00:12:22,910 --> 00:12:23,940
Huh?

197
00:12:25,140 --> 00:12:26,010
Hmm?

198
00:12:26,011 --> 00:12:27,510
Ah, never mind.

199
00:12:38,580 --> 00:12:39,780
Well, then...

200
00:12:42,660 --> 00:12:43,890
Take care of yourself.

201
00:12:47,560 --> 00:12:48,760
I'm off.

202
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:21,500
(Letter of Resignation)

203
00:13:23,780 --> 00:13:26,370
You didn't act out of some grand malice.

204
00:13:26,500 --> 00:13:28,940
You just couldn't help acting
tough in front of your friends.

205
00:13:29,320 --> 00:13:33,840
But because of you,
our lives were completely ruined.

206
00:13:35,900 --> 00:13:39,010
"If you can't forgive them, then don't."

207
00:13:43,340 --> 00:13:48,360
I will hold onto those
words from Kubota-san

208
00:13:48,390 --> 00:13:50,190
and keep moving forward with my life.

209
00:13:55,840 --> 00:13:57,040
Hey, Kasuga?

210
00:13:57,360 --> 00:13:58,560
Kasuga!

211
00:13:59,160 --> 00:14:01,070
Without you, this project is...

212
00:14:01,760 --> 00:14:02,760
Kasuga!

213
00:14:07,260 --> 00:14:08,460
Proposal A and Proposal B

214
00:14:09,360 --> 00:14:10,880
have both been successfully submitted.

215
00:14:13,120 --> 00:14:14,080
We did it!

216
00:14:14,081 --> 00:14:15,241
Thank you for your hard work.

217
00:14:17,650 --> 00:14:18,420
Thank you.

218
00:14:18,421 --> 00:14:20,860
Now, it's up to them to decide.

219
00:14:21,690 --> 00:14:22,690
Yes.

220
00:14:29,500 --> 00:14:32,300
(Mori Naomi: Looking
forward to the broadcast!)

221
00:14:40,510 --> 00:14:41,510
Uh...

222
00:14:42,720 --> 00:14:43,720
Well...

223
00:14:45,120 --> 00:14:49,520
For as long as I can remember,
I was raised in a single-parent home.

224
00:14:51,420 --> 00:14:52,719
Yeah...

225
00:14:52,720 --> 00:14:56,960
My mother was the kind of person
who should've never had kids.

226
00:14:59,600 --> 00:15:01,260
How should I put it?

227
00:15:03,700 --> 00:15:07,900
She completely neglected me.

228
00:15:08,780 --> 00:15:10,869
Since the adults at home never cooked,

229
00:15:10,870 --> 00:15:14,340
I started doing it myself.
That's how I learned to cook.

230
00:15:17,180 --> 00:15:19,250
But I guess it suited me well.

231
00:15:20,960 --> 00:15:26,920
I think I realized I liked guys

232
00:15:28,790 --> 00:15:29,930
when I was in eighth grade.

233
00:15:30,690 --> 00:15:32,190
I had a crush back then.

234
00:15:32,730 --> 00:15:36,630
He was a classmate of mine,
half-Brazilian and half-Japanese.

235
00:15:37,380 --> 00:15:39,340
He was also the first
person I ever confessed to.

236
00:15:40,580 --> 00:15:45,870
But when I confessed,
the look on his face...

237
00:15:46,480 --> 00:15:47,480
Yeah...

238
00:15:48,560 --> 00:15:49,910
It was really something.

239
00:15:51,240 --> 00:15:52,550
How should I describe it?

240
00:15:53,980 --> 00:15:57,790
It was like a zombie or a monster
had suddenly jumped out in front of him.

241
00:15:57,820 --> 00:16:01,920
That's probably the kind of face he made.

242
00:16:03,130 --> 00:16:05,230
I think that's when I
started being openly out.

243
00:16:05,920 --> 00:16:11,470
Because if it's impossible from
the start, I'd rather know sooner.

244
00:16:12,680 --> 00:16:15,100
After that, I just...

245
00:16:15,540 --> 00:16:18,540
fell deeper and deeper into that world.

246
00:16:20,110 --> 00:16:22,180
But honestly, it was easy.

247
00:16:23,620 --> 00:16:27,779
Hooking up with someone,

248
00:16:27,780 --> 00:16:31,590
having a casual, undefined relationship,

249
00:16:32,700 --> 00:16:35,020
and then moving on to the next.

250
00:16:37,320 --> 00:16:39,030
While I was living like that...

251
00:16:41,660 --> 00:16:42,970
When was it again?

252
00:16:45,160 --> 00:16:50,840
I got a message on a dating app from
a guy who seemed really straight-laced.

253
00:16:51,680 --> 00:16:53,310
Oh, do you want to see my private video?

254
00:16:57,580 --> 00:17:00,819
Since I'd been stood up a few times before,

255
00:17:00,820 --> 00:17:03,050
I used to record videos before meeting up.

256
00:17:03,540 --> 00:17:08,560
I didn't think our personalities would
match, but he was totally my type.

257
00:17:09,090 --> 00:17:12,090
So we had a few drinks and went to a hotel.

258
00:17:13,160 --> 00:17:14,230
Well...

259
00:17:17,120 --> 00:17:18,870
Forgive me for being blunt,

260
00:17:18,900 --> 00:17:21,200
but around my private parts,

261
00:17:21,240 --> 00:17:23,140
I have a lot of cigarette burn scars.

262
00:17:24,260 --> 00:17:28,680
My mom's boyfriend did
that to me when I was a kid.

263
00:17:29,260 --> 00:17:30,950
When he saw those scars, he...

264
00:17:35,880 --> 00:17:37,090
actually started crying.

265
00:17:40,200 --> 00:17:44,190
Not long after that,
we moved in together.

266
00:17:44,490 --> 00:17:46,430
It went well at first.

267
00:17:47,020 --> 00:17:51,070
But because I was too carefree,
he started nagging me.

268
00:17:53,260 --> 00:17:54,870
He's actually very ordinary.

269
00:17:55,680 --> 00:17:57,710
Though he doesn't think so himself.

270
00:17:58,000 --> 00:18:02,140
He uses terms like LGBTQ or minority

271
00:18:02,180 --> 00:18:08,080
to define himself,
thinking he's someone special.

272
00:18:09,180 --> 00:18:10,520
But he's not.

273
00:18:11,980 --> 00:18:13,490
He's just normal.

274
00:18:14,620 --> 00:18:16,020
He wants to get married.

275
00:18:16,530 --> 00:18:18,230
He wants kids, too.

276
00:18:18,790 --> 00:18:23,270
He wants social acceptance
and to live in the light.

277
00:18:23,300 --> 00:18:24,800
That's the kind of person he is.

278
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:27,399
Yeah...

279
00:18:27,400 --> 00:18:28,600
But I...

280
00:18:29,510 --> 00:18:30,970
I'm different.

281
00:18:31,690 --> 00:18:35,510
I don't need
society's acceptance or blessings.

282
00:18:36,270 --> 00:18:38,480
Honestly, I find that kind
of stuff to be a nuisance.

283
00:18:39,630 --> 00:18:40,830
So,

284
00:18:43,190 --> 00:18:44,390
two people like us

285
00:18:44,630 --> 00:18:46,490
could never make it work.

286
00:18:46,870 --> 00:18:50,830
Because the things I want to throw away,
he wants to carry.

287
00:18:51,530 --> 00:18:55,860
There was another thing that made
me realize we weren't compatible.

288
00:18:56,630 --> 00:19:04,170
A tropical fish he kept died.

289
00:19:08,010 --> 00:19:11,209
Looking at the fish floating belly-up,

290
00:19:11,210 --> 00:19:14,980
I casually said, "Maybe it
couldn't stand the heat?"

291
00:19:15,880 --> 00:19:19,310
He lost his temper.

292
00:19:23,430 --> 00:19:27,530
The way he said it,

293
00:19:30,270 --> 00:19:35,240
sounded to me like, "How could
a tropical fish not stand the heat?"

294
00:19:38,910 --> 00:19:42,610
I just couldn't accept that.

295
00:19:45,410 --> 00:19:52,690
Because maybe there really is a
tropical fish that can't stand the heat.

296
00:19:55,690 --> 00:19:57,930
Just like how there
are all kinds of gay men,

297
00:19:59,830 --> 00:20:01,900
there should be all kinds of tropical fish.

298
00:20:06,410 --> 00:20:08,170
It died because it was too hot,

299
00:20:13,050 --> 00:20:18,680
yet the person who poured warm water in
buried it, saying, "Poor thing."

300
00:20:21,610 --> 00:20:27,820
I feel like things like that
are happening in every corner of the world.

301
00:20:34,810 --> 00:20:42,240
But the people who will
shape the future of this world

302
00:20:42,730 --> 00:20:44,840
will definitely not be people like me.

303
00:20:46,030 --> 00:20:49,879
It's the ones who long to live in the light

304
00:20:49,880 --> 00:20:51,950
who will change the world.

305
00:20:53,090 --> 00:20:58,350
If the world becomes that warm,
someone like me who can't fit in

306
00:21:00,470 --> 00:21:03,060
will have no choice but
to float belly-up and die.

307
00:21:05,850 --> 00:21:10,200
Of course, I don't plan on stopping it.

308
00:21:11,370 --> 00:21:17,770
But if possible, I hope people won't
forget that someone like me existed.

309
00:21:20,910 --> 00:21:25,410
Even after I'm gone.

310
00:21:32,690 --> 00:21:35,090
So, what do you plan to do next?

311
00:21:37,830 --> 00:21:40,200
Next...

312
00:21:40,250 --> 00:21:41,250
Actually,

313
00:21:42,330 --> 00:21:44,730
I really haven't thought about it.

314
00:21:46,440 --> 00:21:47,870
But...

315
00:21:50,150 --> 00:21:53,680
I don't think I'll ever
reach out to him again.

316
00:21:54,940 --> 00:21:56,010
Hmm?

317
00:22:03,820 --> 00:22:05,020
It's beef bourguignon.

318
00:22:30,430 --> 00:22:32,680
Isn't that obvious?

319
00:22:34,020 --> 00:22:35,450
Of course I'll be lonely.

320
00:22:36,590 --> 00:22:42,420
We just couldn't make it work.
It's not like we hated each other.

321
00:22:45,450 --> 00:22:48,130
I'll be really lonely.

322
00:22:55,610 --> 00:22:57,029
How was it?

323
00:22:57,030 --> 00:22:58,270
Did you get it?

324
00:22:59,070 --> 00:23:01,740
Yes, I got it.

325
00:23:02,580 --> 00:23:04,010
Not that.

326
00:23:05,810 --> 00:23:07,350
Didn't you say it?

327
00:23:08,790 --> 00:23:11,550
That you wanted to make a
video that could change the world.

328
00:23:15,210 --> 00:23:17,030
That was...

329
00:23:20,330 --> 00:23:22,100
Has the world changed?

330
00:23:22,430 --> 00:23:24,470
We don't know the answer to that yet.

331
00:23:24,650 --> 00:23:27,040
That's why I'll keep filming.

332
00:23:27,070 --> 00:23:30,110
Kayano Shiho's eyes
seemed to say it all.

333
00:23:30,140 --> 00:23:31,189
What?

334
00:23:31,190 --> 00:23:32,190
Nothing.

335
00:23:32,570 --> 00:23:33,570
It's nothing.

336
00:23:34,670 --> 00:23:36,480
- Let's go.
- Okay.
